AGI -&nbsp; "Distance on the link with Denmark but without breakage and a decided 'no' to the United States because Greenland is not on sale'". Thus the Italian explorer Robert Peroni connecting via Skype from his study to the 'Red House' in Tasiilaq, a village lost along the east coast of Greenland, commented with AGI the outcome of the legislative elections.
&nbsp;
The Red House is now a symbol of welcoming travellers from all over the world after having been a social project for decades to tear the inuit people from the plagues of alcoholism and the sad world record of suicides. In the white universe, explored by the legendary Knud Rasmussen or Fridjof Nansen, in the 11 March elections, he won the district, a clear message to accelerate towards independence.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The vote has rewarded the democratic party, social-liberal formation with 30.26% of votes. Naleraq nationalists remained at 24,77% while the outgoing government parties, from the left-wing environmentalists of Inuit Ataqatigiit (21,62%) to the Social-Democrats of Siumut (14,88%) had a 15% collapse. Peroni, 81 years old, South Tyrolean native to Renon, lives in Greenland since the early 1980s for a strong, intense, unrelenting love bloomed for the legendary one that in 1983 crossed with the skis towing the sled. A long journey to the discovery of the Inlandeis, the boundless Greenland glacier, challenging the Piterak orchards, the ‘human wind’ which also blows at 250 kilometres per hour.
&nbsp;
“It’s a storm that destroys so much > when it comes is an earthquake, the house trembles all but I feel safe,” he recalls. “Here on the eastern coast we know little or nothing about politics, if I ask someone there is no interest, there is so much illiteracy – says Peroni – On the one hand they want to get away from Denmark, on the other they do not want to go with the United States. The Greenland people want to remain in peace, they are autonomous, they know nothing about war and the European Union. The problem is that if they don't find money, Greenland will still focus on uranium and it would be tragic." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
According to the South Tyrolean explorer, “change little, our government in the last 4 years has been really good but has no experience and internationally can be vulnerable”. Of the members of the Greenland government says, “they are good, they are loyal, they are young, prepared, they did not go to school in Denmark but they studied here.”
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Robert Peroni lives on tourism. After the absolute zero of 2020 and 2021, from 2022 it has been a continuous growth. During Covid, due to the blocking of connections, Peroni in an interview with AGI said he was feeding on expired food. Statements that had made the round of the world and made the fundraising of the 'Save The Red House in East Greenland' campaign on gofund.me (in just over a year more than 100,000 euros were collected).
&nbsp;
“The tourism is good, we have the Red House full >, many Germans and a great boom of Italian tourists, let’s say the best presence ever”, analyzes Peroni that with its activity linked to the ‘Red House’ has saved tens of people.
&nbsp;
“Now there are fewer suicides and also the problem of alcohol in recent years has improved a lot – explains Peroni – I will always remember those many sleepless nights, when they knocked at the door, women, young people, elderly, desperate, without money, cold, alcoholic and hungry. Why do I live up here? Surprised by the welcome of a beautiful, very kind, open, intelligent people, mountains like those of South Tyrol and many glaciers.”
